[2] Minks, culled
Date: Sun 7 Jun 2020
Source: Gelderlander [in Dutch, trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.gelderlander.nl/st-anthonis/sint-anthonis-de-verborgen-nertsenhoofdstad-van-nederland~aaa70b1e/


Everyone know what a farm with cows or pigs they looks like. There are plenty of them in Sint Anthonis. But a mink farm? It is not recognizable as such from the outside; no sign with colorful letters: 'mink breeding'. The animals are not visible.

The world of mink breeding is a closed one. Until about a week ago. Since then, they became frontline, because the minks can become a reservoir for the coronavirus. If the virus continues to circulate among the animals, there is a chance that people get infected through the mink. Therefore, the Ministry of Agriculture decided to clean up the infected farms. The clearing started on Saturday [6 Jun 2020] in Deurne, on Sunday [7 Jun 2020] the clearing teams also came to Landhorst.

A total of 3 companies have been infected in the municipality of Sint Anthonis; all in Landhorst, with one located on the Klotweg [road]. The Klotweg is a dusty dirt road where there has been a request for asphalting for some time. Three other companies seem to be located a little further away, in the outermost area of the municipality. For example, Landhorst probably has 4 and Oploo 3. [map at https://tinyurl.com/ycz493ku].

The CBS website states that there were a total of 128 mink farms in the Netherlands last year [2019], of which 13 are in the municipality of Sint Anthonis - since 2012, 'the mink capital' of the Netherlands. For comparison, in Mill and Sint Hubert there are 4 and in Gennep 3 mink farms.

But after a survey of some residents of Sint Anthonis, it soon becomes clear that nobody knows exactly where the farms are. Jeroen van Acquoij, chairman of the VVD party [People's Party for Freedom and Democracy], would like the municipality to publish this information. "It could be interesting information for residents if they want to stay away from these companies." Because of the privacy of the farms, the municipality will not do this; "to keep the public at a distance," says Van Acquoij.

In a further search for the mink breeders, 4 companies appear the telephone book. So there are still 9 missing. A phone call to the Dutch Federation for Noble Animal Farmers is of little use. They do not want to indicate how many breeding farms there are per municipality. "We will not give this information away without the permission of the owners," said chairman Wim Verhagen.

When asked whether this does not work for animal activists, he replies in the negative: "It is for privacy reasons."

The fear from animal activists seems to make little sense; the Animal Rights organization already has a list of breeding farms in Sint Anthonis. The spokesperson said that 16 companies are emerging.

But how can the activists have 16 companies on their list, while Statistics Netherlands have 13? "Because the industry has to stop in 2024, companies will disappear. Only we can't check if they are still a mink breeder. Some of the locations on our list may now have become goat farms. This can change within a month", said the spokesperson. So there are addresses on the list where there have been no mink for years.

Mink breeding is and will remain a closed world. In any case until [1 Jan 2024]. Then the last mink farms in Sint Anthonis must have disappeared.

[Byline: Mirte van Rooijen]

